revision.text:
{{Culture of Italy}}
As of 2018, two firms in [[Italy]] rank among the world's biggest [[book publisher|publishers]] of [[books]] in terms of revenue: {{illm|Messaggerie Italiane|it}} (including {{illm|Gruppo editoriale Mauri Spagnol|it}}), and [[Arnoldo Mondadori Editore|Mondadori Libri]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/20180917/78036-pearson-is-still-the-world-s-largest-publisher.html |title= The World's 54 Largest Publishers, 2018 |date= 14 September 2018 |work=[[Publishers Weekly]] |location=US |volume=265 |number= 38 }}</ref> Other large publishers include [[De Agostini|De Agostini Editore]].<ref name=PW2017>{{citation |work=Publishers Weekly |location=US |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/international/international-book-news/article/74505-the-world-s-50-largest-publishers-2017.html |title=World's 54 Largest Publishers, 2017 |date= 25 August 2017}}</ref>{{refn|group=nb|Messaggerie and Mondadori also topped the list in 2016 and 2017.<ref>{{citation |work=Publishers Weekly |location=US |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/international/international-book-news/article/71268-the-world-s-52-largest-book-publishers-2016.html |title=World's 52 Largest Book Publishers, 2016 |date= 26 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=PW2017 />}}

==History==
{{see also|Global spread of the printing press#Italy}}

Germans in [[Subiaco, Lazio|Subiaco]], [[Arnold Pannartz]] and [[Konrad Sweynheim]], in 1464 set up a printing press and produced "the earliest book printed in Italy,...a Latin grammar by [[Aelius Donatus|Donatus]]."{{sfn|Peckham|1940}} Printing technology spread in the 1460s to [[Rome]] and [[Venice]]; in the 1470s to places such as [[Bergamo]], [[Bologna]], [[Brescia]], [[Cremona]], [[Ferrara]], [[Florence]], [[Genoa]], [[Lucca]], [[Mantua]], [[Messina]], [[Milan]], [[Modena]], [[Naples]], [[Padua]], [[Palermo]], [[Parma]], [[Pavia]], [[Perugia]], [[Piacenza]], [[Reggio Calabria]], [[Treviso]], [[Turin]], [[Verona]], [[Vicenza]]; and in the 1480s to places such as [[L'Aquila]], [[Pisa]], [[Reggio Emilia]], [[Siena]], and [[Udine]].{{sfn|Proctor|1898}}<ref>{{citation |url= http://data.cerl.org/istc/_index/imprintplace |title= Index: Place of Publication |work=[[Incunabula Short Title Catalogue]]: the International Database of 15th-century European Printing |publisher=[[British Library]] |accessdate= 3 December 2017 }}. (Searchable by town)</ref>

At the time of [[Italian unification]] and the creation of the [[Kingdom of Italy]] in 1861, the Biblioteca Magliabechiana in Florence merged with the {{illm|Biblioteca Palatina Lorenese|it}}, and by 1885 became known as the [[Biblioteca Nazionale Centrale di Firenze]] (National Central Library). The [[Biblioteca Nazionale Centrale di Roma]] formed in 1876. As official [[Legal_deposit#Italy|legal deposit]] libraries, both maintain copies of works published in Italy.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Two National Central Libraries of Florence and Rome |author= Franca Arduini |journal= [[Libraries & Culture]] |volume=25 |jstor=25542277 |year=1990 }}</ref>

The [[United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] named [[Turin]] the 2006 [[World Book Capital]].

